model_output:
Step 1 — E2 elimination to give alkene A
- t-BuOK (a strong, hindered base) effects dehydrohalogenation of (3S)-PhCH2–CH2–CH(Br)–CH3 by an E2 mechanism. The bulky base favors removal of the more accessible β–H and gives the less-substituted (Hofmann) alkene as the major product in this solvent mixture:
  A = PhCH2–CH2–CH=CH2 (IUPAC: 4-phenylbut‑1‑ene).
- The stereocenter at C3 is destroyed when the C3–H/C3–Br are eliminated, so A is achiral.

Step 2 — Hydroboration–oxidation to give alcohol B
- BH3·THF adds across the terminal C=C in an anti‑Markovnikov, syn fashion (BH2 adds to the terminal carbon), and subsequent H2O2/NaOH oxidation converts the B–C bond to an C–OH bond at that terminal carbon:
  B = PhCH2–CH2–CH2–CH2OH (IUPAC: 4‑phenylbutan‑1‑ol).
- B is a primary (non‑stereogenic) alcohol, so it is achiral.

Step 3 — Conversion of alcohol B to alkyl bromide C
- PBr3 converts the primary alcohol to the corresponding alkyl bromide by an SN2‑type pathway. Because the carbon bearing the leaving group in B is primary (not stereogenic), no stereochemical inversion issue arises:
  C = PhCH2–CH2–CH2–CH2Br (IUPAC: 1‑bromo‑4‑phenylbutane, common name: 4‑phenylbutyl bromide).
- C is achiral. (The original (3S) stereocenter from the starting material was lost during the elimination step.)
